In 240 Livius was engaged to produce, as one of the attractions of the ludi Borcani, two Latin plays, a tragedy and a comedy, adapted from Greek originals. Such dramatic entertainments had *for a long time been regularly given in the original Greek in the towns of southern Italy, and so were more or less familiar to the Romans. These performances found such favor at Rome that from this time on they became a regular part of the gamos. Livius Andronicus must then be looked upon as having introduced a new era for the Roman stage. In Livy the historiar (7. 2),Î™ the existence of a connected plot and the systematic arrangement of the contente are designated as the features that distinguished the new drama irem the old satura. It was further distinguished by the employment of Greek metres and by differences in the form of representation. Only a few fragments of the plays of Livius have cerne down to us. We know, however, that he was held in so great esteem at Rome that, in honor of him, the temple of Minerva on the Aventine was appropriated to the use of scribae et histriones, who organized themselves into a sort of poets' guild.
